main event: Local personnel in Antarctica observed an object believed to be an Apollo spacecraft on May 30, 1964.
interesting points: The object was not clearly visible and was not thought to be a meteor.
The report indicates that Apollo had a 30-degree inclination when it went into orbit, so it could not have been seen at 6:30 PM local time on May 31, 1964 in the North Pacific.
The time of the sighting is not mentioned in the report, but the author suggests it was probably the Echo II satellite, as the Navy had reported similar sightings.
The report was a conversation with Sgt. Moody regarding Apollo.
The report is a page from a Project Blue Book record card.
sighted object: An object believed to be an Apollo spacecraft
